    ARTICLE

    Environmental variation associated with topography explains butterfly diversity along a tropical elevation gradient

    View article page
    José Luís Cómbita, Carlos E. Giraldo, Federico Escobar
    format_quote CITE
    © 2021 The Association for Tropical Biology and Conservation
    https://doi.org/10.1111/btp.13040open_in_new
    ISSN0006-3606
    eISSN1744-7429
    Online23 January 2022
    Accepted19 October 2021
    Revised27 September 2021

    Received3 March 2021

    Pages146 - 156
    Abstract

    Few studies have evaluated the role of topography on the diversity patterns of biological communities along elevation gradients. We evaluated the influence of microclimate and vegetation structure associated with topographic variation on the richness and composition of species of different families of butterflies on a mountain located in a dry enclave (Chicamocha River Canyon) in the northern Andes, Colombia. We captured butterflies over four months at 18 elevations (300 to 1500 m a.s.l.) in two topographic positions (riverbed and hillslope) using an entomological net and traps baited with fermented fruit. In general, butterfly richness increased with elevation in both topographic positions. However, the richness–elevation relationship changed with butterfly family. The riverbed and hillslope sites host different assemblages of butterflies, and this pattern that was consistent for most families. In the riverbed, two sets of species are recognized along the elevation gradient (one below 700 m a.s.l. and the other above 1000 m a.s.l.), mainly owing to species replacement. On the hillslopes, there was no clear pattern of grouping associated with elevation. Microclimate differences between the riverbed and hillslope sites along the elevation gradient were related to the vegetation structure and explained the variation in butterfly species composition. Our results highlight the role of topography not only by explaining the response of species richness and composition to environmental variation determined by elevation, but also as a factor that must be considered in the planning and management of biodiversity conservation in the mountains.

    Abstract in Spanish is available with online material.

    Resumen

    Pocos estudios han evaluado el papel de la topografía en la diversidad de las comunidades biológicas en gradientes de elevación. En este estudio exploramos la influencia del microclima y la estructura de la vegetación asociada a la topografía en los patrones de riqueza y composición de especies de diferentes familias de mariposas (Lepidoptera: Papilionoidea) en una montaña ubicada en el cañón del río Chicamocha, un enclave seco al norte de los Andes, Colombia. Capturamos mariposas durante cuatro meses en 18 elevaciones (300 a 1500 m s.n.m.) en dos diferentes posiciones topográficas (fondo fluvial y ladera) utilizando redes entomológicas y trampas con fruta fermentada. En general, la riqueza de mariposas aumenta con la elevación en ambas posiciones topográficas. Sin embargo, la relación riqueza-elevación cambió al considerar la familia. Los sitios en fondo fluvial y ladera albergaron diferentes ensamblajes de mariposas y este patrón fue consistente para la mayoría de las familias. En los fondos fluviales, se reconocen dos conjuntos de especies en el gradiente de elevación (por debajo de 700 m s.n.m. y el otro por encima de 1000 m s.n.m.), determinados principalmente por el reemplazo de especies. Mientras que en las laderas no hubo un patrón claro de agrupación asociado con la elevación. Las diferencias microambientales asociadas con la estructura de la vegetación entre fondo y ladera a lo largo del gradiente de elevación, explicaron la variación en la composición de especies de mariposas. Nuestros resultados resaltan el papel de la topografía no solo para comprender la respuesta de la riqueza y composición de especies a la variación ambiental determinada por elevación, sino también como un factor que debe ser considerado para la planificación y gestión de la conservación de la biodiversidad en las montañas.

| 147CÓMBITA eTAl.2015; Kerr & Packer, 1997; Méndez-Toribio et al., 2016; Moeslund et al., 2013; Quintero & Jetz, 2018; Vasconcelos et al., 2003), few studies have addressed its role along elevation gradients to explain the diversity patterns of the communities that inhabit the mountains (Antonelli et al., 2018; Badgley et al., 2017; Perrigo et al., 2020).Despite the fact that they account for less than 15% of the sur-face of the Earth, mountains host a third of the planet's biodiversity (Myers et al., 2000; Rahbek et al., 2019). One of the mountain re-gions most emblematic for its high diversity and levels of endemism is the tropical Andes (Van der Hammen, 2000). It has been sug-gested that the geological and paleoclimatic history of the Andes, as well as current variations in climate, the elevational stratification of the vegetation and topographic complexity (i.e., steep slopes and valleys of small streams and main rivers that vary in depth), have promoted the diversification and maintenance of a great number of plant and animal lineages with a clear taxonomic substitution of the communities with increasing elevation (Graham, 2009; Hazzi et al., 2018; Hughes & Eastwood, 2006; Rahbek et al., 2019).Of the nearly 9000 butterfly species known in the Neotropics (Raven et al., 2020), at least 40% occur in the Andes (Pyrcz et al., 2014). Several studies show that butterfly richness decreases with elevation, while others report peaks of richness at intermediate ele-vations, though we also know that the richness–elevation relation-ship pattern changes depending on the family of butterflies studied (Acharya & Vijayan, 2015; Hawkins & DeVries, 1996; Janzen et al., 1976; Maicher et al., 2020; Peters et al., 2016; Pyrcz et al., 2014). As in other taxonomic groups, variation in butterfly diversity with increased elevation is related to reduced area and environmental complexity, the greater severity of climate conditions, a reduction in available resources and primary productivity (Hodkinson, 2005; Huston, 1994), and the degree of conservation of the habitats (Molina-Martínez et al., 2016). However, it is known that the mag-nitude of the effects of these factors also depends on the geologi-cal history and topographic complexity of the mountains (Lomolino, 2001; Rahbek et al., 2019; Sanders & Rahbek, 2012).In the mountains, butterfly communities are comprised of spe-cies with narrow elevation ranges, associated with certain lineages of plants on which they depend for food and reproduction (Acharya & Vijayan, 2015; Pyrcz et al., 2009, 2014). Although the factors that determine the diversity of butterfly communities can vary among mountains (Stefanescu et al., 2011), the specific response to envi-ronmental variation is closely linked to the life-history traits of the species, such as their capacity for dispersal, diet and life cycle, hab-itat preference, and thermal tolerance (Cerrato et al., 2019; Habel et al., 2016; Prieto & Dahners, 2006). In this study, we examined the influence of topographic position (riverbed and hillslope) and eleva-tion on the patterns of richness and composition in species of diurnal butterflies (Lepidoptera: Papilionoidea) found on a mountain located in a dry enclave in the northern Andes, Colombia. We addressed the following questions: (a) how does butterfly richness vary when we take into account the microclimate and vegetation structure changes associated with topographic position at different elevations, and do these patterns vary with family? and (b) what is the beta-diversity pattern and its relationship to the environmental conditions associ-ated with topographic position and elevation? Based on our results, we discuss the patterns in the richness–elevation relationship and species composition by butterfly family in response to environmen-tal variations determined by topography.2 | METHODS2.1 | Study areaThe study was conducted at Mesa de Los Santos (6°45′ N, 73°06′ W), which is a large plateau (~430 km2) located in the canyon of the Chicamocha River and is considered the most extensive inter- Andean dry enclave in the Cordillera Oriental, Colombia (Fajardo- Gutiérrez et al., 2015; Pizano & García, 2014) (Figure 1). This canyon is the result of the erosion of the fluvial bed dating back to the early Oligocene (33.9 to 23.03 Ma), with the formation of large ravines on both sides, complex topography with deep, abrupt canyons (maxi-mum depth of 2000 m) that cut through crystalline and sedimentary rock, and are often devoid of vegetation (Guzmán, 2016).The region has a mean annual temperature of 24°C. Precipitation is markedly seasonal and less than 900 mm per year, falling mainly from April to May and August to September (Guzmán, 2016; Valencia-Duarte et al., 2012). The vegetation is tropical dry forest, with a great variety of plant cover types—from xerophytic scrub to areas with trees that are 20 m tall—that change in their struc-ture and composition depending on soil type, the slope and prox-imity to bodies of water (Espinal, 1977; Guzmán, 2016; Holdridge, 1967). According to Camargo-Ponce de León and Agudelo (2017), the Chicamocha River Canyon has had a human presence since pre- Hispanic times and the greatest transformation occurred during the early 20th century. In Mesa de Los Santos, the deepest part of the canyon next to the riverbed is dominated by large trees of Brosimum alicastrum (Moraceae), Anacardium excelsum (Anacardiaceae), Annona squamosa (Annonaceae), Ruprechtia ramiflora (Polygonaceae), and Tabernaemontana grandiflora (Apocynaceae). It is also pos-sible to find some non-native fruit species such as Syzygium jambos (Myrtaceae). The adjacent hillslopes are dominated by sub-xerophytic scrub with the presence of cacti and scattered trees of Myrsine guianensis (Fabaceae), Prosopis juliflora (Fabaceae), Varronia curassavica (Boraginaceae), and Duranta mutisii and Lippia origanoides(Verbenaceae) (Camargo-Ponce de León & Agudelo, 2017; Collazos- González & Echeverry-Galvis, 2017).2.2 | Study designSampling was conducted in 2014 during the dry season between the end of the first rainy period (May) and the beginning of the second rainy period (August) in three microbasins located at least 10 km apart.
